Abstract = {Elinor Ostrom and colleagues developed the social-ecological system
   framework with the aim of synthesizing knowledge to foster a better
   understanding of the relationship between people, institutions and the
   environment. Although the framework has facilitated the diagnosis of
   complex systems; it has thus far struggled to account for the role of
   history in structuring the range of opportunities and constraints that
   actors face as they interact with the environment and each other. More
   recent innovations in measuring institutions and the integration of
   process-oriented approaches are beginning to provide the tools required
   to systematically trace the co-evolution of institutions and
   social-ecological systems. We review the history and development of
   social-ecological system scholarship, including longstanding concerns
   regarding the weak inclusion of temporal dynamics. We highlight the
   contributions of three novel advances - namely the combined IAD-SES
   framework, the institutional grammar tool, and the power in polycentric
   governance approach.},
