Abstract = {One environmental solution proposed by scholars since the 1980s is to
   manage our common natural resources adaptively with emphasis on
   feedback, the inclusion of multiple stakeholders and the flexibility to
   change accordingly. By focusing the analysis on the understudied topic
   of urban river systems in adaptive governance, a systematic literature
   review and a scenario-building exercise were conducted. Whereas the
   bibliometric analysis aims to improve our collective knowledge on many
   aspects of the adaptive management in urban stream governance, the urban
   commoning scenario-building exercise is to simulate alternatives beyond
   conventional top-down management approaches and to explore different
   opportunities of engaging multiple stakeholders throughout the adaptive
   management cycle. Our investigations recommend that although there is a
   trend of considering the ``human{''} or ``soft{''} perspective as part
   of the integrated solution approach, future researches need to ground
   their studies in more empirical cases in order to identify a few
   contextual variables such as ICT or public-private collaboration
