Year = {2022},
Volume = {12},
Number = {1},
Month = {JAN 17},
Abstract = {Managing transboundary river basins requires balancing tradeoffs of
   sustainable water use and coping with climate uncertainty. We
   demonstrate an integrated approach to exploring these issues through the
   lens of a social-ecological system, combining remote and in-situ earth
   observations, hydrologic and climate models, and social surveys.
   Specifically, we examine how climate change and dam development could
   impact the Se Kong, Se San and Sre Pok rivers in the Mekong region. We
   find that climate change will lead to increased precipitation,
   necessitating a shift in dam operations, from maintaining low flows to
   reducing flood hazards. We also find that existing water governance
   systems in Laos, Vietnam, and Cambodia are ill-prepared to address the
   problem. We conclude that the solution space for addressing these
   complex issues will be highly constrained unless major deficiencies in
   transboundary water governance, strategic planning, financial capacity,
   information sharing, and law enforcement are remedied in the next
   decades.},
