Abstract = {Quantification of empirical relationships between ecosystem health and
   human well-being is uncommon at broad spatial scales. We used public
   data for Virginia (USA) counties to examine pairwise correlations among
   two indicators of stream health, thirteen indicators of human
   well-being, and four demographic metrics. Our indicators of stream
   health included the Virginia Stream Condition Index (VSCI) and the
   percentage of stream kilometers with a fish consumption advisory
   (\%FCA); these measures are inversely related. VSCI and \%FCA were
