Volume = {10},
Number = {9},
Month = {SEP},
Abstract = {Blue spaces such as rivers provide many ecosystem services (ES),
   including freshwater for consumption, habitat, water quality regulation,
   and multiple cultural amenities. While many studies have quantified the
   biophysical supply of ES provided by rivers, fewer have explored the
   social demand for ES due to the considerable effort involved in
   collecting these data. The San Marcos River (SMR) and the Texas State
   University (TXST) students that use this blue space represent a dynamic
   social-ecological system (SES) where nature experiences shape student
   values of the system. In this study, we survey the TXST student
   population about their use, value, and perception of the SMR, a highly
   used river of which headwaters originate on and flow through campus.
   From our extensive survey of these students, we find that educational
   and life experiences matter. Overall, we find that student exposure to
   the SMR in space, time, and experience does have measurable effects on
   their use, value, and perception of ES. This SES study demonstrates the
   importance of life experiences, place-based knowledge, and experiential
   learning in influencing one's well-being and value of natural
   environments.},
