   with other social factors such as land privatization and infrastructure
   development, this has reshaped land cover changes over time. In
   response, cattle farming dynamics, especially during critical dry
   periods, have adapted through measures such as switching to greater
   supplementation of commercialfeeds. Despite social-ecological
   transitions, the cattlebased silvopastoral system in the landscape has
   persisted by exhibiting key principles of resilience such as diversity,
   connectivity, andfeedback management. However, concerns on Arther
   impacts ofkey issues (e.g., landprivatization) should be addressed to
   sustain the cattle-based silvopastoral system in the landscape. This
   study provides critical insights on how natural resource management by
   communities andpolicies by decision makers should carefully consider
   their potential impacts in sustaining locally important ecosystem
   services in the face of rapidly transitioning social-ecological systems.},
